\begin_layout Abstract
These notes are dedicated to some thoughts I've had on the Lie derivative.
 A while back when I first saw the definition of the Lie derivative and
 understood nearly nothing about it, William Goldman told me one of those
 facts that just stuck with me.
 Specifically that the Lie derivative of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 may be thought of as the double derivative of the commutator of their respectiv
e flows.
 This seems to be one of those well known facts of differential geometry,
 but I haven't quite found a resource that has the proof in full, so I thought
 I would write it up just in case anyone else out there was just as hopelessly
 lost as I was when I first saw the Lie derivative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First and foremost, everything which follows is assumed to smooth unless
 otherwise stated.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a smooth manifolds of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Given a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $F:M\longrightarrow N$
\end_inset

, we may associate to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 a bundle homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $dF:TM\longrightarrow TN$
\end_inset

.
 This map is sometimes referred to as the 
\shape italic
global differential of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset


\shape default
.
 It is the manifold analogue of the standard differential of a smooth map
 
\begin_inset Formula $G:\mathbb{R}^{m}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and consequently may be thought of as the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
 The global differential makes its appearance almost immediately in any
 introductory differential geometry course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When I first saw the global differential it kind of felt like a power-up
 in a video game.
 Suddenly I could start taking derivatives of any maps I wanted and make
 perfectly good sense of them.
 While to some extent this is true, I remember spending hours upon hours
 trying to reconcile the following question.
 
\shape italic
What is the derivative of a vector field?
\shape default
 This seemingly innocuous question leads to a wealth of very interesting
 mathematics including the notion of 
\shape italic
connections on manifolds
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
Ehresmann connections
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Surely given a smooth vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, it enjoys the property of being a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:M\longrightarrow TM$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\circ Y=\mathrm{id}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\longrightarrow M$
\end_inset

 is the standard tangent bundle projection.
 Consequently the derivative of a vector field makes perfectly good sense,
 and its global differential is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $dY:TM\longrightarrow T(TM)$
\end_inset

.
 And perhaps now you can see some technical difficulties here.
 In particular, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}:T_{p}M\longrightarrow T_{Y_{p}}(TM)$
\end_inset

 is a linear map from the tangent space of the 
\shape italic
manifold
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to the tangent space of the 
\shape italic
tangent bundle of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\shape default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 While this is all theoretically correct, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

, we would like 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 to be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 as well.
 This way for we could for example, make some comparisons between 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I think it's well worth exploring several potential `work arounds' before
 simply giving up and calling it a day.
 For example, perhaps one could take the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)\in T_{Y_{p}}(TM)$
\end_inset

 and identify it with its image under 
\begin_inset Formula $d\pi_{Y_{p}}:T_{Y_{p}}(TM)\longrightarrow T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 This is after all the space we would like 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 to have been in anyways.
 But note that by the chain rule 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d\pi_{Y_{p}}\left(dY_{p}(v)\right)=d(\pi\circ Y)_{p}(v)=d(\mathrm{id})_{p}(v)=v.\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We can see that in our attempt to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 with a vector in the tangent space via the projection map, we've essentially
 disregarded all the data about 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 itself.
 This shouldn't come as too much as a surprise though.
 If you think of derivatives in terms of directions and curves for example,
 we may take a smooth path 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:I\longrightarrow M$
\end_inset

 representing 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, wherein 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime}(0)=v$
\end_inset

.
 In so doing, 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y\circ\gamma)^{\prime}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that this may be thought of as taking the time derivative of the vector
 field along 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

.
 I think this perspective provides some insight into the difficulties here.
 Specifically, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

 may be thought of as a lift of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 to the tangent bundle.
 In terms of commutative diagrams, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\xymatrix{ & TM\ar[d]^{\pi}\\
I\ar[ur]^{Y_{\gamma}}\ar[r]_{\gamma} & M
}
\label{eq:2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Now note that as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 varies, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}\in T_{\gamma(t)}M$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in I$
\end_inset

.
 That said, if we think about 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 as a bundle over 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, we can see the difficulty in differentiation.
 The curve 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

 is changing fibres of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:TM\longrightarrow M$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 varies which translates to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

 lying in different tangent spaces for different 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Ideally, one would like to try and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dY_{p}(v):=\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(Y_{\gamma(t)}-Y_{p}\right).\label{eq:3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

But notice, that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{p}$
\end_inset

 lie in different tangent spaces, and thus it makes no sense to subtract
 them.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Figure-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below illustrates this difficulty.
 Moreover, when we compose 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

 with the projection map, we simply end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(Y_{\gamma(t)}\right)=\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

, thus eliminating all information pertaining the vector field in question.
 The vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 tells us what vectors to assign each value of 
