\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}$
\end_inset

, whereas the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 tells us which direction along the manifold we're evaluating 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in.
 This sort of mode of thought helps lead to the notion of an 
\shape italic
Ehresmann connection
\shape default
, which is in essence a way to split 
\begin_inset Formula $T(TM)$
\end_inset

 into two bundles, one a vertical bundle corresponding the kernel of the
 map 
\begin_inset Formula $d\pi:T(TM)\longrightarrow TM$
\end_inset

, and a horizontal bundle complementary to the vertical bundle.
 The vertical bundle is well defined independent of the connection, whereas
 the horizontal bundle is a choice that in essence allows us to decompose
 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 into a vertical and horizontal component.
 More details about this can be found in some excellent notes by Timothy
 Goldberg, 
\shape italic
What is a Connection, and What is is Good For?
\shape default
 [1]
