\begin_layout Standard
To conclude this section, I would like to point out there are situations
 where these difficulties do not arise.
 Specifically, in the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we have the tangent bundle naturally identifies with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The first factor may be thought of as the manifold component, whereas the
 second factor may be thought of as the tangent space component.
 In this situation, a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:\mathbb{R}^{n}\longrightarrow T\left(\mathbb{R}^{n}\right)\simeq\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}\circ Y=\mathrm{id}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{1}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{n}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is projection onto the first factor.
 Consequently the first factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the identify, and that said, we may as well identify 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 as map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:\mathbb{R}^{n}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to the second factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now to each tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{n}\simeq\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, we may take the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

.
 Motivated by Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), let us represent 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 by the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=\left(\gamma^{1}(t),\ldots,\gamma^{n}(t)\right)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(0)=p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime}(0)=v$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, let us express 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 in coordinates by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(q)=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y^{1}(q),\ldots,Y^{n}(q)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Returning to Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
dY_{p}(v) & =\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(Y_{\gamma(t)}-Y_{p}\right)=\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(Y^{i}(\gamma(t))-Y^{i}(p)\right)e_{i}=\frac{\partial Y^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}(\gamma(0))\frac{d\gamma^{j}}{dt}(0)e_{i}\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\frac{\partial Y^{1}}{\partial x^{j}}(p)\frac{d\gamma^{j}}{dt}(0),\ldots,\frac{\partial Y^{n}}{\partial x^{j}}(p)\frac{d\gamma^{j}}{dt}(0)\right),\label{eq:4}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the third equation in the top row follows by the chain rule applied
 to the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\circ\gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Note that Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) provides us with a notion of a derivative of a vector field in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and moreover, it's kind of what anyone would guess, namely just differentiate
 the components.
 At face value, this really just appears to be an exercise in coordinate
 expansions.
 In fact, it's worth trying to see how this translates over in the general
 case of a manifold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For an arbitrary manifold, we no longer enjoy the ability to have a global
 trivialization of the tangent bundle, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily identified with 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, we still enjoy local trivializations of the tangent bundle.
 So that said, for a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, pick a chart 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\phi)$
\end_inset

 about it where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:U\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism onto some open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This induces a local frame for the tangent bundle given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \partial/\partial x^{i}\right\} $
\end_inset

, so we may express a vector field, at least locally about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.Y\right|_{q}=Y^{i}(q)\left.\partial/\partial x^{i}\right|_{q}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in U$
\end_inset

.
 In addition if we pick a 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

, we may express it in terms of this frame as 
\begin_inset Formula $v=v^{j}\left.\partial/\partial x^{j}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 That said, we may try and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dY_{p}(v):=\left.v^{j}\frac{\partial Y^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}(p)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i}}\right|_{p},\label{eq:5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

just as we did in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:4"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) where each 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{j}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $d\gamma^{j}/dt(0)$
\end_inset

.
 As with most constructions on manifolds, we would ideally like to ensure
 this quantity is well defined independent of coordinate patch.
 To this end, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi)$
\end_inset

 is another coordinate patch, with coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}^{k}$
\end_inset

, we note that have the equations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.Y\right|_{q}=Y^{i}(q)\left.\partial/\partial x^{i}\right|_{q}=\tilde{Y}^{k}(q)\left.\partial/\partial\tilde{x}^{k}\right|_{q}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=v^{j}\left.\partial/\partial x^{j}\right|_{p}=\tilde{v}^{l}\left.\partial/\partial\tilde{x}^{l}\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Their coordinates are related by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y^{i}(q)=\tilde{Y}^{k}(q)\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}(q)\text{ and }v^{j}=\tilde{v}^{l}\frac{\partial x^{j}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{l}}(p).\label{eq:6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Differentiating the first equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{i}(q)$
\end_inset

 and suppressing the evaluation at at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial Y^{i}}{\partial x^{j}}=\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{j}}\left(\tilde{Y}^{k}\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\right)=\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{\partial}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}\left(\tilde{Y}^{k}\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\right)=\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{\partial\tilde{Y}^{k}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}+\tilde{Y}^{k}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}.\label{eq:7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:7"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) back into Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) with the change of coordinate for 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{j}$
\end_inset

 in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:6"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
dY_{p}(v) & =\tilde{v}^{l}\frac{\partial x^{j}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{l}}\left(\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{\partial\tilde{Y}^{k}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}+\tilde{Y}^{k}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i}}\nonumber \\
 & =\tilde{v}^{l}\left(\frac{\partial x^{j}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{l}}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\right)\frac{\partial\tilde{Y}^{k}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}\left(\frac{\partial x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i}}\right)+\tilde{v}^{l}\tilde{Y}^{k}\left(\frac{\partial x^{j}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{l}}\frac{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}{\partial x^{j}}\right)\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i}}\nonumber \\
 & =\tilde{v}^{l}\delta_{l}^{m}\frac{\partial\tilde{Y}^{k}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}}\frac{\partial}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}+\tilde{v}^{l}\widetilde{Y}^{k}\delta_{l}^{m}\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{m}\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i}}\nonumber \\
 & =\tilde{v}^{l}\frac{\partial\tilde{Y}^{k}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{l}}\frac{\partial}{\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}+\tilde{v}^{l}\tilde{Y}^{k}\frac{\partial^{2}x^{i}}{\partial\tilde{x}^{l}\partial\tilde{x}^{k}}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{i}}.\label{eq:8}
\end{align}

\end_inset

While these calculations are quite lengthy, they do provide some insight
 into what goes wrong in our definition.
 If we compare Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:8"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) with Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we see precisely what goes wrong.
 In particular, the presence of this second term in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:8"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is an obstruction to this quantity being well defined independent of coordinat
e chart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That said, we should take the time to consider why this works in the case
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and not a general manifold.
 Note that in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:8"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), if we hypothetically had our manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 covered with a coordinate atlas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \left(U_{\alpha},\phi_{\alpha}\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that the change of coordinates had vanishing Hessian, then Equation
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is well defined, and this derivative is dependent on the coordinate atlas.
 In fact a very natural class of manifolds to look at for which this works
 are 
\shape italic
affine manifolds
\shape default
.
 Affine manifolds are a class of manifolds whose change of coordinates are
 locally affine maps, namely maps from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=Ax+b$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathrm{GL}(n,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 For those of you familiar with connections, it's worth verifying this derivativ
e corresponds to the pullback connection of the standard connection on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another case where we may define the derivative of a vector field without
 necessarily deferring to the machinery of a connection is in the case where
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is parallelizable, that is, there's a bundle isomorphism between 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 As per consequence a vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:M\longrightarrow TM$
\end_inset

 is the same a having a smooth map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:M\longrightarrow M\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the identity on the first component.
 Consequently, the data of a vector field is really just a map 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:M\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We may now define 
\begin_inset Formula $dY_{p}(v)$
\end_inset

 to be as in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), where the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}-Y_{p}$
\end_inset

 makes sense now as per consequence of the global trivialization of the
 tangent bundle.
 Certainly we may always trivialize locally, as we attempted to in Equation
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:8"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 But it seems unreasonable to have this difference quotient depend on local
 identifications, whereas it's far more palatable for it to depend on a
 single fixed identification.
 That said, it is perhaps again worth emphasizing that such a definition
 is indeed still relying on a choice, in particular, here we are relying
 on an identification between 
\begin_inset Formula $TM$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\times\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and in general this identification is non-canonical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Lie Derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the above discussion, it may seem hopeless to define a meaningful
 derivative of a vector field on a manifold.
 One of the main issues is the inability to compare tangent spaces.
 This is a fundamental difficulty of differential geometry and has been
 studied extensively.
 In fact, one will often find calculus problems about 
\shape italic
rolling without slipping
\shape default
 which are intimately related to notions of identifying tangents spaces
 at different points via a construction known as 
\shape italic
parallel transport
\shape default
.
 The idea is parallel transport provides us a means of identifying tangent
 spaces at different points via curves on the manifold.
 Certainly how one travels along the manifold, will in general, impact these
 identifications.
 Take for example the two curves on the sphere and in Figure 
