\begin_layout Standard
Motivated by this idea of looking at identifications between tangent spaces,
 one is perhaps led to consider the diffeomorphism group of a manifold.
 If we want to make sense of the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}-Y_{p}$
\end_inset

, we need some way of identifying tangent spaces.
 Diffeomorphisms certainly provide this.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 taking a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to another point 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, then the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $dF_{p}:T_{p}M\longrightarrow T_{q}M$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism between vector spaces.
 Now let's say we have a path of diffeomorphisms, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{t}$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{t}(p)=\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

.
 This provides us with identifications of 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\gamma(t)}M$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(F_{t}\right)_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Under the circumstances we can't necessarily make sense of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}-Y_{p}$
\end_inset

, but it seems then natural to consider the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(d\left(F_{t}\right)_{p}\right)^{-1}\left(Y_{\gamma(t)}\right)-Y_{p}.\label{eq:9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Before proceeding, let's make sure this is a reasonable quantity.
 Certainly 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\gamma(t)}\in T_{\gamma(t)}M$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, since 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(F_{t}\right)_{p}:T_{p}M\longrightarrow T_{\gamma(t)}M$
\end_inset

, we know the inverse map, which is well defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a diffeomorphism, takes 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\gamma(t)}M$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the quantity in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:9"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) does indeed make sense.
 Moreover, it is feasible that we could then take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(\left(d\left(F_{t}\right)_{p}\right)^{-1}\left(Y_{\gamma(t)}\right)-Y_{p}\right).\label{eq:10}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a general path of diffeomorphisms, one should not expect the above to
 converge, as we have no control over what 
\begin_inset Formula $d\left(F_{t}\right)_{p}$
\end_inset

 does at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 for example, it's merely a map that fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 under our current stipulations.
 In addition, how does one obtain a path of diffeomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(F_{t}\right)_{p}=\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

 represents a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

 ?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A very natural context to take into consideration is flows on a manifold.
 Given a one parameter subgroup of a diffeomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{t}:\mathbb{R}\longrightarrow\mathrm{Diff}(M)$
\end_inset

, one knows that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}=\mathrm{id}$
\end_inset

, and thus the behavior at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, and ideally locally about 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, must be reasonably controlled.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the above observations, it's not entirely outlandish then then try
 and differentiate a vector field with respect to another vector field as
 vector fields define local flows.
 That said, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be vector fields on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 For the sake of simplicity, I'm just going to assume their corresponding
 flows are indeed complete, though the following constructions and arguments
 may be adapted to purely local arguments.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is the vector field we wish to differentiate, 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the vector field we intend to differentiate along, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta:\mathbb{R}\times M\longrightarrow M$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding flow map of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, and we wish to define the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, in a similar fashion to Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:10"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Denoting this derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\mathcal{L}_{X}Y\right|_{p}$
\end_inset

 we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left.\mathcal{L}_{X}Y\right|_{p} & :=\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(\left(d\left(\theta_{t}\right)_{p}\right)^{-1}\left(Y_{\theta_{t}(p)}\right)-Y_{p}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(d\left(\theta_{-t}\right)_{\theta_{t}(p)}\left(Y_{\theta_{t}(p)}\right)-Y_{p}\right),\label{eq:11}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}^{-1}=\theta_{-t}$
\end_inset

.
 Several facts need to be verified and will not be provided in these notes,
 the most pressing being that this vector field is indeed well defined.
 For those interested in further detail, and where much of the notation
 and inspiration for these notes has been drawn from, I refer you to Jack
 Lee's outstanding differential geometry text 
\shape italic
Introduction to Smooth Manifolds
\shape default
 [2].
 This book is a really solid general reference for the material, and his
 conversational writing style, thoroughly detailed arguments, and illustrations
 make this one of those texts I just roundly recommend to everyone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before continuing it worth pointing out the definition as in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is very different than the one provided in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:5"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Recall the method of identification relating 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\gamma(t)}\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 was via the identification induced by translation taking 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Here though the identification between 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\gamma(t)}\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the flow of a vector field.
 The following examples serve to illustrate this difference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:Example-1"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
X=-y\frac{\partial}{\partial x}+x\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\text{ and }Y=\frac{\partial}{\partial x}.\label{eq:12}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(x,y)$
\end_inset

 and let us calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{X}Y$
\end_inset

.
 Deferring to Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we first calculate the flow of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, one can show with relative ease that the corresponding system
 of differential equations is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{\prime}=-y\text{ and }y^{\prime}=x\text{ where }(x(0),y(0))=(x,y)\Longrightarrow\theta_{t}(x,y)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos(t) & -\sin(t)\\
\sin(t) & \cos(t)
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

That said, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\theta_{t}(p)}=\left.\partial/\partial x\right|_{\theta_{t}(p)}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\left(\theta_{-t}\right)_{\theta_{t}(p)}\left(Y_{\theta_{t}(p)}\right)=d\left(\theta_{-t}\right)_{\theta_{t}(p)}\left(\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{\theta_{t}(p)}\right)=\left.\cos(t)\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{p}-\left.\sin(t)\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right|_{p}.
\]

\end_inset

The minus sign is because we are using the inverse flow, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{-t}$
\end_inset

, and not 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging this result into Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:11"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{X}Y=\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{1}{t}\left(\left.\cos(t)\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{p}-\left.\sin(t)\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right|_{p}-\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{p}\right)=\left.\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{\cos(t)-1}{t}\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{p}-\left.\frac{\sin(t)}{t}\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right|_{p}=-\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial y}\right|_{p}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

