\begin_layout Standard
It should be mentioned there is yet another formulation of the Lie derivative
 in terms of vector fields acting on the algebra of smooth real-valued functions
 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Specifically, given two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 on a manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, one may define the Lie-bracket of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to be the vector field which acts on the algebra of smooth real-valued
 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $(XY-YX)f=X(Yf)-Y(Xf)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathrm{C}^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the following formulation of the Lie derivative is substantially more
 computationally accessible, and theoretically advantageous to work with,
 it suffers the serious draw back of not enjoying any `obvious' geometric
 interpretation, at least to my knowledge.
 In fact, that it the above even defines a vector field is far from obvious
 in my opinion.
 Nevertheless, it allows one to calculate Lie-derivatives with relative
 ease and has a straightforward coordinate representation.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are locally given in coordinates by 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X^{i}\partial/\partial x^{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=Y^{j}\partial/\partial x^{j}$
\end_inset

, then the Lie-bracket of these two vector fields is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{X}Y=[X,Y]=\left(X^{i}\frac{\partial Y^{j}}{\partial x^{i}}-Y^{i}\frac{\partial X^{j}}{\partial x^{i}}\right)\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{j}}.\label{eq:15}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That this definition and the formulation in terms of derivatives of flows
 agree is far from clear, but nevertheless one may find a proof of this
 in Jack Lee's text [2].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Derivative of Commutator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As promised in the summary, we conclude by providing a proof that the Lie
 derivative of vector fields 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is given by the second derivative of the commutator of their flows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 have flows given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Pick a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in M$
\end_inset

, and a coordinate patch centered about 
