\begin_inset Formula $(V,\psi):V\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume this coordinate patch is sufficiently small so that there's a box
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(-\epsilon,\epsilon)^{2}$
\end_inset

 for which both 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 are defined everywhere in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 This stipulation is to guarantee that the flows do not blow up in finite
 time, and instead become undefined only in so far as they leave the open
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 As this discussion is purely local, we may assume in fact identify 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with an open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 centered at the origin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\phi_{-t}\theta_{-t}\phi_{t}\theta_{t}\right)(0):(-\epsilon,\epsilon)\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 If we Taylor expand both 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta:(-\epsilon,\epsilon)\times$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $V\longrightarrow V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{t}:(-\epsilon,\epsilon)\times V\longrightarrow V$
\end_inset

 about the origin, we have the following 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\theta(t,x)= & \theta(0,0)+\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}(0,0)t+\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}(0,0)x+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial t^{2}}(0,0)t^{2}\right.\nonumber \\
 & \left.+\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial t\partial x}(0,0)tx+\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial x\partial t}(0,0)tx+x^{T}\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial x^{2}}(0,0)x\right)+\ldots\nonumber \\
= & 0+\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}(0,0)t+\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}(0,0)x+\frac{1}{2}\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial t^{2}}(0,0)t^{2}+\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial x\partial t}(0,0)tx+\frac{1}{2}x^{T}\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial x^{2}}(0,0)x+\ldots\label{eq:16}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where here I'm being very abusive in notation.
 In particular, the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\partial^{2}\theta/\partial x^{2}\right)(0,0)$
\end_inset

 is supposed to denote the second derivative of a vector valued function
 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 took values in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, you get the standard Taylor expansion of a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and this quantity represents the Hessian matrix.
 In our case though, this is a tensor quantity, which nevertheless can be
 recovered by doing Taylor expansions on each 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{i}$
\end_inset

 in the coordinate expansions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\left(\theta^{1},\theta^{2},\ldots,\theta^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately I don't know if there's a standard notation for this, so
 I just kind of made up my own, but if you need any convincing of what this
 is, just consider the two by two case from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and write out the details to see exactly what it is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may calculate the derivatives in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:16"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), as they reduce quite a bit.
 Recall the first input of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the time coordinate, whereas the second input is the spatial coordinate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have the following equalities 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}(0,0) & =\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\right|_{t=0}\theta(t,0)=X(0),\label{eq:17}\\
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial x}(0,0) & =\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{x=0}\theta(0,x)=\mathrm{id},\label{eq:18}\\
\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial t^{2}}(0,0) & =\left.\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial t^{2}}\right|_{t=0}\theta(t,0)=\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\right|_{t=0}X_{\theta_{t}(0)}=\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0)X(0),\label{eq:19}\\
\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial x\partial t}(0,0) & =\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{x=0}\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\right|_{t=0}\theta(t,x)=\left.\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\right|_{x=0}X(x)=\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0),\label{eq:20}\\
\frac{\partial^{2}\theta}{\partial x^{2}}(0,0) & =\left.\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}\right|_{x=0}\theta(0,x)=\left.\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}\right|_{x=0}x=0.\label{eq:21}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:17"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) follow immediately from the relation between vector fields and the induced
 flow, namely the flow differentiates in time to the vector field.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:18"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is a consequence of the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(0,x)$
\end_inset

 is the identity map on the space, so its derivative is the identity map
 on tangent spaces.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:19"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is again a consequence of the properties of flows, but where the last
 equality follows from the chain rule applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\circ\theta)(t,0)$
\end_inset

.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:20"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is straight forward and follows more or less by definition.
 Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:21"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) follows again by consequence of the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(0,x)$
\end_inset

 is the identity map on the space, so its second derivative vanishes.
 To be convinced of Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:21"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) it helps to think of the array of second derivatives of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}\right)\mapsto\left(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The first derivative may be thought of as the identity matrix, and differentiat
ing the components of a matrix with constant values should yield zero.
 Combining the results of Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:17"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)-(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:21"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) provides the second order Taylor expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

 below.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta(t,x)=x+t\left(X(0)+\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0)x\right)+\frac{t^{2}}{2}\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0)X(0)+\ldots\label{eq:22}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The same holds true for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi(t,y)=y+t\left(Y(0)+\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}(0)y\right)+\frac{t^{2}}{2}\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}(0)X(0)+\ldots\label{eq:23}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Composing Equations (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:22"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:23"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we may calculate the commutator of the flows at 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in V$
\end_inset

.
 As these calculations are pretty intense, I used Mathematica, see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Figure-6"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below for the exact code.
 In particular, this yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\phi_{-t}\theta_{-t}\phi_{t}\theta_{t}(0)=t^{2}\left(\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}(0)X(0)-\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0)Y(0)\right)+\ldots\label{eq:24}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the remaining terms are all of higher order in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and thus vanish for the second derivative evaluated at zero.
 Differentiating and evaluating at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left.\frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}\right|_{t=0}\left(\phi_{-t}\theta_{-t}\phi_{t}\theta_{t}\right)(0)=2\left(\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}(0)X(0)-\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0)Y(0)\right).\label{eq:25}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Up to the factor of two, the right hand side in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:25"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) in coordinates is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial Y}{\partial x}(0)X(0)-\frac{\partial X}{\partial x}(0)Y(0)=\left(\frac{\partial Y^{j}}{\partial x^{i}}(0)X^{i}(0)-\frac{\partial X^{j}}{\partial x^{i}}(0)Y^{i}(0)\right)e_{j},\label{eq:26}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the form of Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) above.
 This concludes the proof.
