\begin_layout Standard
It is perhaps worth noting that you may raise objections to this in so far
 as we're taking second order derivatives.
 Certainly the first derivative of a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:I\longrightarrow M$
\end_inset

 lies in the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\gamma(0)}M$
\end_inset

, but not the second.
 The reason why we may consider the second derivative to be an element of
 the tangent space is extremely subtle.
 Let's say you have a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:I\longrightarrow M$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 In general tangent vectors of curves act on the algebra of smooth functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime}(0)f=(f\circ\gamma)^{\prime}(0)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ\gamma:I\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a smooth function.
 Because the first derivative vanishes, we may actually define an action
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime\prime}(0)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(M)$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime\prime}(0)f=(f\circ\gamma)^{\prime\prime}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 In general this does not satisfy the criterion of being a derivation, but
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime}(0)=0$
\end_inset

, it does.
 It is worth writing out the technical details to ensure that this is so,
 but once this is verified, we may indeed identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{\prime\prime}(0)\in T_{p}M$
\end_inset

.
 In our case, one can see via Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:24"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) that this condition is satisfied, as the commutator possesses no first
 order terms.
\end_layout

